{"/service/ndnp/whi/batch_whi_italico_ver01/data/sn83045293/00542869276/1930010301/0261.xml":{"full_text":"Page Seven\nThe Labor Movement \u2014The Socialist Party\nANTI-SOCIALIST\nFEELINS CROWS\nLESS IN BRITAIN\nLONDON The relaxation of\nChristmas week has written a no\nticeable change in the atmosphere\nof British politics. The bitterness\nand threats of overthrowing the\nMacDonald Socialist government\nwhich marked the closing session\nof parliament on Christmas eve\nhave faded out in the interval since\nand the new year this week is be\nginning with a general desire not to\nharass the government in the midst\nof its rapidly developing difficul\nties in fields outside England.\nThere is a new aspect in the pre\nlimaries to tiie naval conference\nproduced by the French memoran\ndum, the ultimatum from China\nconcerning the immediate abolition\nof extraterritoriality and above all\nthe Indian situation.\nTo Change Coal Bill.\nOn the other hand, the domestic\nqucslfcn of coal legislation which a\nweek ago promised to make serious\nt rouble for the government has been\nniatermlly smoothed by assurances\nfrom William Graham, president of\nthe board of trade, that the coal\nbill will he modified in such a way\nas to offset the objections of the\nLiberal party in the house of com\nmons. Therefore, the recent predic\ntions that this government is ap\nproaching its finish and that a gen\neral election will be necessary be\nfore Easter are for the time being\ndiscarded\nThe most significant evidence of a\nchanged atmosphere lies in the fact\nthat there is no disposition to hold\nthe MacDonald government respon\nsible for the crisis in India precipi\ntated by the determination of the\nNational Congress of Labor to de\nmand immediate independence, to\nrefuse to participate in the round\ntable conference with British dele\ngates on dominion status and to\nbring about civil disobedience, in\ncluding the refusal to pay taxes.\nSympathy for Viceroy.\nRecent criticism of Lord Irwin,\nthe viceroy, for his assurance that\ndominion status is still the ultimate\naim of the British government for\nIndia have been swallowed up by\nexpressions of sympathy for the\nviceroy because of the attempt to\nassassinate him.\nThat ultimate dominion status for\nIndia is the avowed aim of the\npresent government as well as its\npredecessors in Whitehall is one of\nihe most obvious facts of British\nempire politics. There is nothing\nanticipated to the contrary in the\nSimon commission\u2019s report, which\nwill be ready for submission soon\nafter parliament reconvenes on Jan.\n21. The chief difference at the\npresent moment which is all in fa\nvor of the Indian Nationalist aspi\nrations is that with the MacDonald\ngovernment, the word \u201cultimate\u201d\ndoos not imply such a vague and\nremote time in the future as it has\nunder preceding administrations.\nHope of Premier.\nIt is really the hope and objective\nof Prime Minister MacDonald and\nhis secretary of state for India,\nWedgwood Benn, Socialist, to for\nmulate a system in the round-table\ncons efence and an accord with the\nIndians themselves whereby a new\nconstitutional life and freedom for\nt hat country will be achieved in\nthe reasonably near future. There\nis no doubt that the attainment of\n1 his objective will be delayed rather\nthan hastened if the present threats\nof the Lahore congress prove effec\ntive.\nThere is no tendency in England\nto minimize the gravity of the situ\nation. which is freely admitted to\nbe the most serious matter the coun\ntry has faced since 1914. But there\nare no war hysterics. The public\nlias not yet reached the stage of\nvisualizing crowded troop ships hur\nrying east across the Indian ocean.\nHas New Complexion.\nStrangely enough, the Indian\nquestion is not, as in 1924, being\nmixed tip with the government\u2019s\npolicy of slowing down work on the\nSingapore naval base and with pe\nriodical warnings of what Russia\nmay do against Britain in the whole\nAsiatic field. Neither in the pres\nent crisis is the threatened uprising\nin India being attributed to soviet\npropaganda.\nBritain\u2019s hopes for the best out\ncome, not unmixed with fears of\nthe worst, are based on the fact\nthat the Lahore congress represents\nnot more than 20,000 Indians, an\ninfinitesimal fraction of a popula\ntion of 400,000 000 and that outside\nof the congress there are other na\ntive leaders who are advocating the\nmoderate course of giving Britain\neven more time to grant constitu\ntional reforms in line with Nation\nalist aspirations. Furthermore, it\nis assumed that Mahatma Gandhi,\nwho has now placed himself at the\nhead of the most radical groups,\nlias laid down a program which is\ninherently impossible of accomplish\nment because of his demand that\nthere be widespread civil disobedi\nence and a boycott of everything\nBritish without violence.\nLook for Violence.\nThe more probable outcome is\nthat there will be much violence on\nboth sides, with the result that the\nEnglish jieople will be less inclined\ntn grant what they are now willing\n\u2022ro grant and the Indians will be\nsubmerged in a new wave of bitter\nness and less willing to accept what\nis offered.\nThe constructive reform recom\nmendations of the Simon commis\nsion, which is just completing the\nmost comprehensive survey of India\never undertaken, will, it is feared,\ni>e made public when both countries\nare in no mood to consider them.\nAdopt 5-Day Week\nIn Frisco Building\nSAN FRANCISCO\u2014In San Fran\ncisco the five-day week for build\ning trades is now in effect. The\nsame wage scale per day will ap\nply, with holiday overtime pay for\nSaturday mornings. It applies to\nnil artisans except in mechanical\nemergency repairs\nSr\ni\u2014.\nTODAY.\nNorth Side Younjr People\u2019s Socialist\nleague, Jefferson hall, 2649 Fond du Lac\nave.\nNorth Milwaukee branch. Community\nhall. North Milwaukee ave. and Thirty\nseventh st.\nWest Allis branch, Kralj\u2019s hall, Ufty-\nUrst ave. and Sherman st.\nGesangvereln \u00a3delweiss, Stubbnig's\nball, 2229 Brown st.\nGesangvereln Bavaria, Barden Maen\nnerchor hall. Ninth and Winnebago sts.\nOest.-Cngarnischer Gesangvereln, 654\nTwelfth st.\nFifteenth Ward branch, 339 Twenty\nsixth st.\nImportant Notice.\nAll members who have sold tick\nets for the Socialist Winter Shows\nare kindly asked to send the money\nto Al. Benson, 528 Juneau ave.\nKindly remit as soon as possible for\nall tickets sold.\nY. P. S. L. Mask Ball.\nThe Young Peoples\u2019 Socialist\nleague will hold a prize mask ball\non Saturday evening, Feb 22, 1930,\nat the Jefferson hall, Twenty-sev\nenth st. and Fond du Lac ave. (No\ntice to branches: Please do not\nmake conflicting dates.)\n25th Ward Branch.\nThe 25th Ward branch of the So\ncialist party will hold its annual\ncard party, Sunday, Feb. 9, 1930.\nThe games will include skat, 500,\nsheepshcad, cinch and rummy. (No\ntice to ^ranches: Please do not\nmake conflicting dates.)\n7th Ward Branch Card Party.\nA prize card party at which all\ngames will be played will be held\nWednesday evening, Jan. 22. 1930,\nat the Bahn Frei hall, Twelfth st.\nand North ave. High grade prizes\nto all winners. All games 35 cents.\nA cordial invitation is extended to\nall.\n22nd Ward Branch Card Party.\nThe 22nd Ward branch will hold\na prize card party consisting of\nskat, sheepshead, 500, cinch and\nrummy at the Jefferson hall, 2649\nFond du Lac ave., March 8, 1930, at\n8 p. m. (Notice to branches: Please\ndo not make conflicting dates.)\nElection of Officers.\nThursday evening, Jan. 9, 1930,\nthe 24th Ward branch will elect of\nficers and install them for the com\ning year. The committee has ar\nranged for music and refreshments.\nAll members are urged to attend.\nThe meeting will be held as wsual\nin Peter Sinkowski\u2019s hall, 889 Mus\nkego ave.\nSouth Side Women\u2019s Branch.\nThe South Side Women\u2019s branch\nwill hold a card party Tuesday aft\nernoon, Jan. 7, at 2:30 p. m., in\nPossl\u2019s hall, Sixth and Greenfield\naves. All members and friends are\nwelcome.\nBay View Women\u2019s Branch.\nUntil further notice the Bay View\nWomen\u2019s branch will meet at Guen\nther\u2019s residence, 235 Howell ave.\nMeetings will be held same as\nusual, every second Wednesday of\nthe month, while card parties will\nbe held on the fourth Wednesday\nof the month. At the next meet\ning, Wednesday, Jan. 8, officers\nwill be elected. Members are urged\nto attend.\nSecond Ward Branch.\nThe Second Ward Branch will\nrun a skat, sheepshead, cinch and\n500 card party Sunday, Feb. 23, at\nMiller\u2019s hall, Eighth and State sts.\nOther branches please take note and\ndo not conflict with date.\nY. P. S. L. Meeting.\nA regular meeting of the Young\nPeoples\u2019 Socialist league will take\nplace Friday evening, Jan. 3, in the\nJefferson hall, 2649 Fond du Lac\nave. Officers for the new year will\nbe elected. All members are urged\nto attend.\nLeader Women\u2019s Card Party.\nThe Milwaukee Leader Women's\nclub will hold its second card party,\n1:45 p. m., Jan. 14, at the Eagles\u2019\nclub, 2401 Wisconsin ave. Refresh\nments will be served. Valuable\nprizes will be awarded for high\nscores. Tickets may be obtained at\n50 cents from Mmes. Charles J.\nEbert, phone Concord 1497-W; Wal\nter Palm, Concord 2628; 11. E.\nSteele, Orchard 7006-R; Philip\nWenz, Locust 5703; George Kostiz,\nKilbourn 9727; A. J. Walker. Con\ncorl 1532-W; Joseph Kluchesky,\nConcord 1030.\n20th Ward Branch.\nThe 20th Ward branch has ar\nranged to hold its annual mask ball\nin Schmidt\u2019s hall, Twenty-fourth\nand Hopkins sts., on Saturday night.\nFeb 8. Admission 25 cents. A good\ntime is assured to all. North side\nbranches are requested not to make\nconflicting arrangements for this\ndate.\nStrike of Garment\nWorkers Postponed\nNEW YORK\u2014Originally sched\nuled for Jan. 1, the strike of 45,000\nwomen's garment workers is not\nlikely to take place for at least two\nweeks. It may be called off entire\nly, this possibility hinging on the\nresult of conferences now in prog\nress.\nAUTO MECHANICS\nINSTALL HEADS\nOfficers of the Auto Mechanics\u2019\nunion No. 510 will be installed at\na meeting at 296 West Water st.,\ntonight.\nCarl Franz will be inducted as\npresident.\nOthers to be installed are:\nVice president, E. Martin; record\ning secretary, Frank Moore; finan\ncial secretary, Marvin Shoemaker;\ntreasurer, Frank Brandt; trustees,\nLeo Wright, George Kast< i and\nHerbert Horn delegates \u2018o the Fed\nerated Trades council. Franz, R.\nStuckert and George Washechek.\nASSAIL COURT\nHANDLING OF\nWORKERS\u2019 RISK\nNEW ORLEANS That commis\nsion rather than court administra\ntion is indispensable sos the satis\nfactory operation of a workmen's\ncompensation law, w T as the em\nphatic declaration made here yes\nterday by compensation experts\nmeeting at the closing session of the\n23rd annual convention of the\nAmerican Association for Labor\nLegislation.\nCourt administration as attempt\ned in a few states is a failure,\ncharged the prominent authorities\nattending the convention. That\ncourt administration is a fraud\nupon the injured worker, an injus\ntice to the employer, and wasteful\nto the community, was their com\nmon conclusion.\nLeaves Workers Helpless.\nFrances Perkins, recently- promot\ned by Gov. Roosevelt from the New\u2019\nYork Industrial board to her pres\nent position as industrial commis\nsioner, presided. Commissioner Per\nkins emphatically denounced court\nad m i nistration of compensation\nlaws. \u201cSuch a system,\u201d she de\nclared, \u201cleaves the worker practic\nally helpless. The few states which\nuse this method may pretend to\nhave accepted the compensation\nprinciple, but actually they have\nwithheld the real substance.\u201d She\npointed out that the International\nAssociation of Industrial Accident\nBoards and Commissions, and the\nAssociation of Government Officials\nin Industry, as weil as the Ameri\ncan Association for Labor Legisla\ntion, have gone on record as\n\u201cstrongly in opposition to such mis\nleading legislation.\u201d\nSeven Out of 44.\nCommissioner T. A. Wilson of\nNorth Carolina pointed out that\nonly seven of the 44 state compen\nsation laws still attempt to admin\nister wor km e n\u2019s compensation\nthrough the courts. Several states\nwhich once utilized the court sys\ntem, he declared, have abandoned it\nfor the more effective method of\ncommission administration. \u201cCourt\nadministration is slow, complicated\nand costly,\u201d he said, \u201cand tends, be\ncause of its inherent difficulties, to\ndefeat the very purpose of work\nmen\u2019s compensation.\u201d\nSpeaking on the Theory of Work\nmen\u2019s Compensation, Dr. Witte of\nWisconsin said that American com\npensation acts were passed for prac\ntical, not theoretical, reasons; and\nthat these practical considerations\nall related to the unsatisfactory\nconditions under the old damage\nsuit system.\nOrigin of Plan.\n\u201cWorkmen\u2019s compensation was\noriginated,\u201d said Dr. Witte, \u201cto af\nford workmen an appreciably larger\nrecovery, a recovery fixed, prompt,\nand certain, without the necessity\nfor legal action. It w\u2019as also in\ntended to relieve employers from\nthe possibility of being ruined by\nexorbitant awards for negligence\nand/to withdraw the entire problem\nfrom the realm of dispute with em\nployes. Finally, it was designed to\ninterest employers in preventing ac\ncidents.\u201d\nDr. John B. Andrews, secretary\nof the association, commented on\nthe prospects of compensation leg\nislation in the coming year. \u2018\u2018There\nare now only four states, all in the\nsouth, which do not have workmen\u2019s\ncompensation laws,\u201d he said. \u201cThey\nare Arkansas, Florida, Mississippi\nand South Carolina. In each of\nthese states, workmen\u2019s compensa\ntion is being strongly advocated.\u201d\nProf. Noel G. 'Dowling of Colum\nbia university law school, and Isaac\nHeller, New Orleans attorney, also\nspoke.\nParis Chambermaids\nAsk Definite Wage\nPARIS Repairing by the hun\ndreds from apartments great and\nsmall to the left bank of the Seine,\nthe Parisian femmes de menage, or\nchambermaids, drew up a bill of\nrights yesterday for presentation to\nthe households they serve.\nIt reads:\n\u201cFrom now on, we must have a\nfixed wage, not depending on the\nwhim and humor of our employ\ners.\u201d\nThe regular wage of these maids\nof all work in Paris is sl2 to sl6 a\nmonth.\nBarbers 9 Meeting\nWill Be Tuesday\nJoint installation exercises of the\nBarbers\u2019 union No. 50 and the Mas\nter Barbers\u2019 Assn, will be held Tues\nday instead of Monday.\nAn article in The Milwaukee\nLeader recently inadvertently\nstated that the exercises would be\nheld Monday.\nA dance will be conducted at the\nBlatz hotel in connection with the\nexercises.\nLabor Meetings\nTODAY.\nAsbestos Workers No. 19. 808\nWalnut st., 8 p. m.\nBill Posters and Billers No. 12,\nMusician's hall, 532 Edison st., 7:3U\np. m.\nElevator Constructors No. 15,\nBahn Frei hall, 861 Twelfth st, 8\np. m.\nEngineers (Hoisting and Port\nable) No. 139, Lipp\u2019s hall, 8 p. m.\nAuto Mechanics No. 510, room 13,\nMechanic\u2019s hall, 296 West Water st.,\n8 p. m.\nBakers Union No. 52. Belfor hall,\nEleventh and Walnut sts.\nPattern Makers Assn., Brisbane\nhall, 8 p. m.\nPlasterers No. 138, 808 Walnut\nst., 8 p. m.\nMaster Mates and Pilots Union\nNo. 51, 98 Ferry st.. 8 p. m.\nTOMORROW.\nBakers No. 205, 205 Brisbane\nhall, 5:30 p. m.\nTHE MILWAUKEE LEADER, FRIDAY, JANUARY 3, 1930.\nU. S. LABOR DEPT.\nSAYS BUSINESS\nOUTLOOK IS OK\nWASHINGTON \u2014Vast construc\ntion programs already formulated\nand expected business expansion\npromise to make 1930 a \u201csplendid\nemployment year,\u201d the department\nof labor declared.\n\u201cRoad construction and public\nimprovements will exceed by many\nmillions the 1929 program,\u201d Direc\ntor General Jones of the depart\nment's employment service pointed\nout in a special report on the 1930\nemployment outlook.\nReferring to the momentary loss\nof confidence that followed the\nstock market break, Jones added:\n\u201cBut the vigor and strength of\nthe nation are evidencing them\nselves, and after a careful survey of\nthe business outlook we enter the\nnew year with an optimistic spirit\nand high hopes, and predict that\n1930 will measpre in volume of\nbusiness with the preceding year.\n\u201cT he ex t e nsive improvement\nplans of the major ralroads will af\nford much employment in their\ncanstr action, maintenance and\nequipment! division.\n\u201cThe automotive industry for the\nmoment is marking time, but the\nlarge manufacturers are optimistic\nwith the prospect of a volume of\nbusiness equal, to that of the year\njust ended.\n\u2019\u201clt is expected that all building\ncraftsmen will not be able to find\nemployment until early spring.\nHowever, it is believed that build\ning in 1930 should compare favor\nably with 1929.\nPHOENIX SIGNS\nOP WITH UNION\nAn agreement with the American\nFederation of Full Fashioned Ho\nsiery Workers has been signed by\nthe I\u2019hoenix Hosiery Co., 114 Buffa\nlo st., it was announced yesterday.\nA similar agreement was signed\nby the Holeproof Hosiery Co. re\ncently.\nThe signing of the agreement\nwill prevent the bringing about of\nconditions which have caused labor\ntroubles in mills in Kenosha and\nIndianapolis, it is believed.\nHarold E. Steele, secretary of\nthe federation local, is in Philadel\nphia and could not be reached.\nJohn E. Fitzgibbon, general manag\ner of the firm, said that no change\nIn operating methods will be neces\nsitated by the agreement.\n7 Killed, 24 Hurt,\nToll Inflicted on\nSouthern Strikers\nAt the end of seven months\u2019\nstruggle to organize, the strikers\u2019\ntoll is six men and one woman\nkilled, 24 wounded, seven sentenced\nto prison for five to 20 years, seven\nkidnaped and five flogge\u2019 by mobs.\nNot a single one of those responsi\nble for the violence against the\nstrikers has been brought to jus\ntice.\nThe case of the textile workers\nagainst the state of North Carolina\nstands as above, according to the\nAmerican Civil Liberties union,\nsays a writer in the current issue\nof Nation. The article continues:\n\u201cThe eight deputies lately on trial\nfor second degree murder for the\ndeath of six textile workers have\njust been acquitted by a moun\ntaineer jury in Burnsville, N. C.\nThe strikers were shot in the back;\nnot one of them, according to eye\nwitnesses, carried a gun; the depu\nties used their guns to disperse a\ncrowd in front of one of the mills\nat Marion.\n\u201cTheir plea was self-defense\u2014\nagainst an old man, James Jones,\nnow dead, who, after the sheriff\nhad thrown tear-gas bombs into the\ncrowd, began to Jay about him with\nhis cane, against two or three un\narmed workers who had shown no\ndisposition to violence and even\nwhen they were shot at had only a\ndesire to get away.\n\u201cThe verdict was not a surprise\nto spectators in the courtroom, nor\nwill it be to anyone who has fol\nlowed the mill trials so far. The\nstate always wins; the strikers and\norganizers always lost. But the\nstate may rest assured that, while\nlabor conditions in the south re\nmain what they are now, the bloody\nNew Year Brings\nDisaster to Miner\nWASHINGTON\u2014Just as whistles\nbegan to blow to usher in 1930, the\nfamily of \u2018Walter Krachek, a Mead\nowlands coal miner, heard a noise\nin the cellar of their home. The\nhouse shook and trembled as though\nin an earthquake. Rushing down\nstairs, Krachek arrived in time to\nsee the last of his furnace disap\npearing into a great hole in the\nearth. The house began to topple\nand the miner lost no time rushing\nhis family outside.\nFlames soon licked their way\nthrough the lower floor of the frame\nstructure and the edifice became a\nmass of ruins, as a blazing tribute\nto the passing of the old year.\nTimbers beneath the house had\ngiven way and the furnace had\ndronped into an abandoned mine\nshaft.\nKrachek carried insurance on the\nhouse and contents.\nTeamsters 9 Strike in\nChicago Cancelled\nCHICAGO\u2014The strike of Chicago\ncoal teamsters and chauffeurs\u2019\nunions, which was called for yes\nterday, was cancelled when union\nmen and the Coal Dealers\u2019 Assn, de\ntermined to continue present work\ning agreements pending discussion\nof differences. Had the strike gone\ninto effect the city would have\nfaced a coal famine within 48 hours,\nit was said.\nPREDICTS EARLY\nPOLITICAL UNION\nOF LABOR IN U. S.\nNEW YORK\u2014The inevitable po\nlitical organization of labor in\nAmerica will come soon, according\nto a prediction by Reinhold Niebuhr\nin The World Tomorrow.\nIn America, as in Great Britain,\nwhere labor has had great victories,\n\u201clabor desires a functional social\nized democracy in which wooden\nshoes and polished boots will be\nmatters of taste and not a sign of\nlocation on the scale of participa\ntion in the good things of life,\u201d Mr.\nNiebuhr writes.\nState Action Hampered.\nWhether in matters of income\nand inheritance, of natural re\nsources, labor disputes, unemploy\nment, or any of the other problems\nclustered about the conduct of in\ndustry and the welfare of indus\ntrial populations, points out this\nwriter, wise action by the state is\nhampered by individualistic tradi\ntions which the social and political\nfacts render increasingly anachron\nistic, but which the powerful and\nprivileged groups find it to their\nadvantage to maintain.\nIt is only as the masses of toilers,\nincreasingly dispossessed by inex\norable trends in commerce and in\ndustry, neutralize the effects of cen\ntralization of power and privilege,\nand strive for control of the politi\ncal life of the nation, that any\nmeasure of justice may be estab\nlished.\nHas Helped Little.\nAccording to Mr. Niebuhr, the\nAmerican Federation of Labor by\nits concentration on economic ac\ntion and refusal to enter politics\nhas helped labor little.\nAmerican labor, be says, has not\nwon a richer share of the rewards\nof industry than other labor; the\nrewards have been richer and, even\nthough inequitably distributed, those\nwho receive least have received\nmore than laborers in other nations.\nMore Stabilized\nCondition Sought\nIn Clothing Trade\nNEW YORK\u2014The noteworthy\nfeature of the banquet held several\nweeks ago to celebrate the fifth an\nniversary of the resumption of ar\nbitration in the New York men\u2019s\nclothing industry was the stress\nlaid by all the speakers on the need\nfor a more stabilized industry.\nLeading retailers of the country,\nclothing manufacturers, and the\nunion all joined in making a public\nplea for greater co-operation among\nthe responsible factors in the in\ndustry.\nIt is a far cr from discussion of\nthe generalities of industrial rela\ntions to the consideration of such\nproblems as the credit risks of the\ncustomers of woolen mills, the evils\nof cancelation, and the public ad\nmission by large distributors of the\nvalue of labor organizations.\nLieut. Gov. Lehman said that sta\nbilization of this type of industry\nwas inconceivable without a strong\nand responsible trade union; and\nSidney Hillman of the Amalgamat\ned Clothing Workers went so far as\nto predict the creaation of an in\ndustrial council, composed of all the\nelements of the industry, which\nshould utilize its moral force for\nthe control of those who refuse to\ncontribute to the welfare of the in\ndustry.\nA survey of the operations of the\nimpartial machinery, made by Jacob\nBillikopf, the impartial chairman,\nshowed how much progress has been\nmade toward the peaceful adjust\nment of disputes and toward higher\nstandards of living in the industry\nas a result of the introduction and\nsuccessful administration of unem\nployment insurance.\nFEDERAL LABOR\nUNION ELECTS\nTHIEN AS HEAD\nI Edward Thein was elected presi\ndent of Federal Labor union. No.\n17710, in Liedertafel hall, 702 High\nland ave., last night.\nSimon De Bruin was re-elected\nrecording secretary.\nOther new officers are: Vice\npresident, Gerhard Rades; financial\nsecretary-treasurer, O. R. Work\nmeister; guide. William Uecker;\nguard, James Finch; chief steward,\nR. D. Carey, and trustees, R. D.\nCarey, Frank Boncel; George Hop\nper, Arthur Oehlke and Adolph\nWischen and steward, R. D. Carey.\nDr. Coif man Denies\nOffer From Illinois\nMINNEAPOLIS, Minn.\u2014Dr. Lo\ntus D. Coffman, president of the\nUniversity of Minnesota, today de\nnied reports that he had been of\nfered a position as head of the Uni\nversity of Illinois. Dr. Coffman said\nhe had received no formal proposal\nfrom Illinois representatives and\nthat he was negotiating with no\nother institution.\nENGLISH PAPER\nTO CARRY ART\nTO LABORERS\nLONDON\u2014In an endeavor to\n\u201ccarry art to the workers,\u201d at\nreasonable prices, The Daily Her\naid, organ of the Labor party,\nannounced today that it would\nreceive orders for postcard-size\nreproductions of the famous Ital\nian masterpieces now on exhibi\ntion at Burlington house, from\nreaders who are unable to attend\nthe brilliant showing. The minia\ntures will cost 4 cents apiece,\nand The Daily Herald will pay\nthe postage\nFILM OPERATORS\nSEEK SIX-DAY\nWEEK WITH PAY\nCHICAGO\u2014New contract negoti\nations were begun yesterday be\ntween the Moving Picture Operators\u2019\nunion and the Exhibitors\u2019 Associa\ntion of Chicago.\nThe union, through Tom Malloy,\nchairman of its wage committee,\naksed the theater owners for the\nshortening of the operators\u2019 work\nweek one day, without any cut in\npay.\nThis would amount to the same\nas an increase of 15 per cent in sal\naries, according to Jack Miller,\npresident of the association. The\npresent contract expires at mid\nnight, Saturday night, Jan. 11.\nThe operators now 7 are paid from\nSBO to as high as $l5O a week in\nsome instances. The rate is based\non seating capacity of theaters and\nthe admission charge.\nNEGRO TO GET\nAID OF A. F. L.\nWASHINGTON The American\nFederation of Labor is ready to\nhelp the Negro to organize and\nraise his standards, the federation\nreported.\nAn editorial to be published in\nthe January issue of the American\nFederationist, of which William\nGreen, president of the organiza\ntion, is president, said the first at\ntack upon the industrial problem of\nNegroes was by organization and\nthe second by vocational training.\nDiscussing a national Negro labor\nconference sponsored by the sleep\ning car porters\u2019 union, to be held\nin Chicago this month, the editorial\nsaid:\n\u201cOrganization is the new way to\nstatus Industry, higher wages, just\nand honest working conditions,\nshorter hours of work. These things\nare essential to higher social and\npolitical standing.\n\u201cTrade union membership is open\nto all Negroes. The majority of\ntrade unions accept Negroes as\nmembers, but when regulations are\ninterposed the rules of American\nFederation of Labor provide that\nNegro workers may apply for a\ncharter direct from the American\nFederation of Labor.\u201d\nSAFETY MATCHES\nARE GIVEN OUT\nBY CIGARMAKERS\nFifty thousand boxes of safety\nmatches are being passed out to\nsmokers by the Cigarmakers\u2019 union\nof Milwaukee.\nEach box bears the caution in\nlarge letters: Smoke Union Made\nCigars and Promote Home Indus\ntry.\nThe union always has made It a\npoint to supply various conveniences\nto the public, as part of Its all-year\nadvertising campaign. During the\nbaseball season vest pocket sched\nule cards are issued.\nThe boxes of matches now being\ndistributed have the additional\nmerit, as set forth on the label, that\nthey are \u201cmade in the U.S.A, by\nAmerican workers, of American ma\nterials for the American climate.\u201d\nAMUSEMENTS.\nContinuous, 11 A. M. to Midnight\nNOW!\nYour beloved favorites\nTOGETHER in a riot\nous, madcap comedy!\nIt\u2019s all fun!\nn ^ary\nDOUGLAS\nlairbankt\nIB\n'\u2019AMINO\nW 01 Illi\nSHRCW'\nBAViDSON-NOW\nMAT. TOMORROW\u2019, SOc to >1.50\nI ou?NOBLE EXPERIMENT BAR\nI The Smashing Hit of th\u00ae Year\nI one more\nI WEEK 17*4 1 dl*ld dim\nHELD OVER\nThe tremendous ovation that\nMilwaukee has given\n\u201cAFTER\nDARK\u201d\nhas made It necessary that we\nhold this sensational success\nONE MORE WEEK\nPOSITIVELY THE LAST\nWEEK HEBE!\nZENITH THEATERI\nWALTER HOUSTON\nin \u201cTHE LADY LIES\u201d\nALL-TALKING\nSound News \u2014Sound Review\u2014All-\nTalking Comedy\nLabor Organizer Is\nKidnaped, Charge\nCHARLOTTE. N. C.\u2014Elbert Tot\nerow, international labor defense\norganizer, was kidnaped from a\nLumberton, N. C., hotel yesterday\nby a group of textile mill workers.\nC. W. Summey, unionist, reported\nhere today. Summey said Toterow\nwas taken from the room which\nthey jointly occupied and \u201cspirited\nout of town in an automobile.\u201d\n2 Million Jobless\nToday in Germany\nBERLIN Approximately 2.000,-\n000 persons are out of work in Ger\nmany as the new year opens. Offi\ncial records list 1,400,000 receiving\nfull doles. The other 600.000 are\nlooking for jobs but do not belong\nto unions entitled to relief. Berlin\nalone has 271,330 unemployed re\nceiving doles, or 50,000 more than\nlast year.\nMISHAP DELAYS\nSTART OF HUNT\nFOR AVIATORS\nNOME, Alaska\u2014One Eielson res\ncue expedition had today met with\na temporary setback.\nIn attempting to take off from\nFairbanks for Nome, one of the\nFairchild monoplanes of the Avia\ntion corporation rescue unit ground\nlooped on the flying field and was\ndamaged.\nThe name of the pilot, who was\nseriously hurt, was not learned.\nThis expedition is in charge of\nCapt. Pat Reid.\nThe other two planes, brought\nfrom Seattle on a coast guard cut\nter, were held at Fairbanks, and\ndid not attempt a take-off because\nof weather conditions.\nFrank Dorbrandt, Alaska Air\nways pilot, and \u201cbuddy\u201d of the\nmissing airman. Carl Ben Eielson,\nhas recently suffered a nervous\nbreakdown, believed to have been\ncaused by the strain of worry over\nhis comrade\u2019s fate, and he has been\nrelieved from duty. He will fly to\nFairbanks from here, abandoning\nplans for a solo rescue flight.\nA Russian expedition was quar\ntered at Petropavlosk, awaiting the\nend of the arctic winter to add its\ntwo Junkers planes to the steadily\nincreasing list of searchers for Eiel\nson and his mechanic, Earl Borl\nand, now missing seven weeks near\nNorth Cape.\nSoviet Sends Fifth Man.\nMOSCOW\u2014Another soviet avia\ntor, M. M. Gromov, was ordered to-\nAMUSEMENTS.\nI HAROLD LLOYD\n\u201cUNTAMED\u201d I\nE mTx \u2018bRADfJeLD \u201cWELCOME DANGER\u201d\nn Vow Master of Ceremonies in A Paramount Release\nCecil B. DeMille\u2019s Mighty Drama\n\u201cDYNAMITE\u201d\nWith CONRAD NAGEL, KAY JOHNSON,\n^os^ CHARLES BICKFORD and JULIA FAYE\n1\nFarwell at North 27th at Wells\nKING VIDOR\u2019S EPIC\n\u201cHALLELUJAH!\u201d\nWith\nNINA MAE McKINNEY J\nThe New Sensation! It\u2019s the Lowdown on Oar Highbrows! I\nMICKEY MOUSE CARTOON\nFOX-MOVIETONE NEWS\u2014Air Glider Pilot Falls to Death i\nHoliday Spirit Inspires Great Chorus\nitl a niMha mi j ?i a IdU\nMWehell at 7th Near Locust\n40th at North Mitchell at\nSir Arthur Conan Doyle\u2019s\n\u201cTHE RETURN OF SHERLOCK HOLMES''\nWith\nCLIVE BROOK\nLeo Reisman\u2019s Hotel Brunswick Orchestra\n\u201cGUNBOAT GINSBURG\u201d\u2014 Comedy\nFOX-MOVIETONE NEWS\nItalian Rulers Pay First Visit to Pope.\nMODJESKA, 6 to 7 P. M.; UPTOWN OOp\nand GARFIELD, 6:30 to 7 P. M UVV\nMODJESKA\u2014MMnIte Show Tomorrow, 11:30 f.\nPOULTRY, PIGEON and\nRABBIT SHOW\nand Gauntry Fair\nAuditorium, Jan. 1\u20142 \u20143\u20144 \u20145\nBuick Sedan and 200 Other\nValuable Prizes Free.\nEducational and Entertaining.\nPoultry and Eggs Free\nEvery Afternoon and Evening.\nOpen 9 A. M. to 10 P. M.\nADMISSION BOc; CHILDREN 23c.\nrauDNiAf\nALL-TALKING\nDOLORES COSTELLO\nin \u201cHEARTS IN EXILE\u201d\nTalking Comedy\u2014Act\u2014News\nALHAMBRA\nDOLORES DEL RIO\nAS\n\u201cEVANGELINE\u201d\nCity Club Auspices\nAnnounce Lectures\nComing in January\nAccording to announcement made\ntoday by the City club, outstanding\nlectures will be given under the aus\npices of the club in January.\nPeter Witt, Cleveland, a student\nof politics, will speak on England,\nthe English People and the Last\nElection at a dinner to be held in\nthe club at 6 p. m. Wednesday.\nIn a lecture discussing frontier\ntypes, Lew Sarett, woodsman-lectur\ner-poet will present Slow Smoke in\nSt. John\u2019s auditorium, 500 Jackson\nst., at 8 p. m. Jan. 16.\nAt a dinner at 6 p. m. Jan. 23,\nDr. Herbert Spencer Dicky, medical\nofficer for sugar estates, mining\ncompanies and railways in South\nAmerica since 1900, will lecture on\nMisadventures of a Tropical Medico\nat the club.\nThe Wonderland of Plants will be\npresented by Arthur C. Pillsbury at\n8 p. m. Jan. 28, in SU John\u2019s ilakU\ntorium.\nShorewood Leads\nSuburbs in Tax\nPayments to Date\nThe village of Shorewood leads\nin collection of suburban taxes, ac\ncording to reports from suburban\ncity treasurers.\nThe village has taken in $65,178\nsince Nov. 22. A total of $923,308\nis to be collected.\nWauwatosa takes second place.\nAccording to Fred Prudisch, treas\nurer. the city has collected $57,134.\nCudahy, South Milwaukee and\nWest Allis started collecting taxes\nyesterday. Whitefish Bay, which\nhas been collecting since Dec. 26,\nhas taken in $20,360.\nLove for Sale\u2014Love powders\nwere advertised for sale during the\nmiddle ages. Love-philtres were\nkept by the village apothecary\namong his stock of drugs. These\nlove potions were compounded of\nsuch lovely things as snails and in\ngredients that go to make up our\nvilest bootleg of today and frequent\nly resulted in similar effects.\nday to proceed to Khabarovsk to\nparticipate in the aerial search for\nthe missing American flier, Capt.\nCarl Ben Eielson.\nBoris Chuknovsky and his three\ncompanions of the famous Red Bear\nquartet were due to reach the Kras\nnoyarsk late tonight en route to\nhunt for Eielson, off the Siberian\ncoast.\nAMUSEMENTS.\nGARDEN 3RD WEEK\n100 Real Stars\n\u201cShow of Shows\u201d\nAll In Color\nMAJfSTID ROW\nLUPE VELEZ in\n\u201cTIGER ROSE\u201d\nSupported by an All-Star Cast\nR KO RIVERSIDE\nHe's In the Cavalry Now!\nWILLIAM BOYD\nin \u201cHIS FIRST COMMAND\u201d\n\u2014On the Stage\u2014\nROSE\u2019S 25 LILLIPUTIANS\n100% Talking\u2014Singing\n\u201cGo!d-Di\"gers of Broadway\u201d\nWith NICK LUCAS mid WINNIB\nLIGHTNER\nEntirely in Natural Color\nPage Seven","height":"29139","width":"21519"}}
